But the most striking illustration ol the bishop in Gascoigne’s age is to be found in a story which he tells of De la Bere, Bishop ol St. David's (p. 35). This man had been Henry’s almoner, had been made Dean of Wells by papal provision (p. 200), and had caused infinite scandal by the appointment. To put an end to the scandal, the same agency of a papal provision was brought into operation, and De la Bere was made Bishop ol St. David’s. ‘About the years 1452 and 1453, the rectors, vicars‚ and priests of Wales, who had concubines with them in their houseS, said to their Bishop of St. David's, “O lord bishop, we, the priests of your diocese, drawn by the sear of God and the dread of eternal punishment to come on sinners, beseeeh your latherhood, that by your pontifical authority you cause or compel our concubines to go away, and be perpetually separated from us and our homes, lor we beg and pray that they may be so separated from us and our homes by your authority, that we may never have opportunityof sinning with them, and these concubines may never have an opportunity of sinning by cohabiting with us.'’ And that bishop os detestable memory’ (he outlived Gaseoigne) ‘answered them, “I will not grant that your con· cubines be separated srom you or your homes, orbe compelled to leave them, lor in that case, l your bishop should yearly lose 400 marks, which Ι receive yearly in my diocese sor the priests’ concubines, lor
